				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$200\,\upmu \hbox {mol m}^{-2}\,\hbox {s}^{-1}$$\end{document}200μmolm-2s-1, respectively) (Parrine et al. 2018). Such a high light intensity exposure was accompanied by heat production up to \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$120\,^{\circ }\hbox {C}$$\end{document}120∘C at the leaf surface. As a result damages in the photosystem pathways were described in combination with an oxidative stress response.

For cultivated tomatoes a highly orchestrated temperature regime depending on the developmental stage is discussed (Boote et al. 2012; Shamshiri et al. 2018). It includes optimal temperature ranges of 18–\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$21\,^{\circ }\hbox {C}$$\end{document}21∘C during night and 21–\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$30\,^{\circ }\hbox {C}$$\end{document}30∘C during day for all developmental stages (Camejo et al. 2005; Shamshiri et al. 2018), and especially \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$22\,^{\circ }\hbox {C}$$\end{document}22∘C as being optimal for the vegetative state (Sato et al. 2000; Adams et al. 2001), and 24–\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$25\,^{\circ }\hbox {C}$$\end{document}25∘C for optimized leaf area expansion, shoot elongation and plant biomass (Ntatsi et al. 2014), in addition to fruit development and maturation (Adams et al. 2001). In this regard, the applied warmer temperature regime was still in the optimal temperature range for tomato development.

In addition, we identified genes known to be involved in secondary metabolism such as: Solyc05g053550.3.1, a chalcone synthase, and Solyc10g052500.2.1, an isoflavone reductase homolog, in S. lycopersicum, and Sopen10g032910.1, a flavonol-3-O-rhamnosyltransferase, in S. pennellii. Among the further identified genes from the weighted cluster analyis, we found three putative uridine 5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
